{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17520700","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17520700"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:27:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:27:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13429"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13429","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13429"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.41,0.24,0.15,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6037"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52910"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6037","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6037"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13429"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38300"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"181"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4061"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11012"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11317"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14813"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15374"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34405"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52910","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52910"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man is attending an outpatient appointment for drainage of his ascites which has been refractory to diuretic use. His medical history includes cirrhosis secondary to chronic alcohol abuse diagnosed five years ago, though he has reportedly been abstinent for the past three months. Since diagnosis, he has been admitted on multiple occasions for symptomatic ascites and encephalopathy in the setting of infections, as well as one incident of variceal bleeding two years ago. His current medications include carvedilol, furosemide and spironolactone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he is alert and has icteric sclera. His blood pressure is 105/68 mmHg, pulse 96/min, temperature 37.4\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC and SpO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E 96% on room air. His JVP is elevated at 5 cm and there are bilateral basal crackles heard on pulmonary auscultation. His abdomen is distended, with shifting dullness and a positive fluid thrill. Bilateral peripheral oedema is noted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis most recent and relevant investigations include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAST of 130 U/L (10-40 U/L)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EALT of 60 U/L (7-56 U/L)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBilirubin: 42\u00b5mol/L (3-20)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EINR: 1.5 (\u0026lt;1.1)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlbumin 30g/L (\u0026gt; 30)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn abdominal CT scan confirms cirrhosis with signs of portal hypertension and large oesophageal varices. His eligibility to undergo a transjugular intrahepatic portosystemic shunt (TIPS) is discussed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be the strongest indication for this procedure?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["History of encephalopathy","His refractory ascites","The previous episodes of variceal bleeding","Signs of decompensated congestive heart failure","His Child-Pugh category"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe transjugular intrahepatic portosystemic shunt (TIPS) procedure is a minimally invasive procedure that involves inserting a stent to connect the portal veins to adjacent blood vessels, allowing blood flow to bypass the liver to lower portal pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe two indications with the strongest evidence for the TIPS\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eprocedure are secondary prevention of oesophageal variceal bleeding and treatment of \u003Cstrong\u003Erefractory ascites,\u003C/strong\u003E which are both present in this clinical scenario, but the ascites is the more recent and relevant management problem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAbsolute contraindications for the TIPS procedure include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESevere congestive heart failure, tricuspid regurgitation or pulmonary hypertension\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUncontrolled systemic infection or sepsis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnrelieved biliary obstruction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary prevention of variceal bleeding \u003C/strong\u003Eto reduce the risk of bleeding and mortality typically involves treatment with non-selective beta-blockers (i.e. propranolol or carvedilol), whereas the TIPS procedure is indicated for secondary prophylaxis of variceal bleeding (i.e. patients who recovered from an episode of haemorrhage and required prevention for recurrent variceal bleeding).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESevere congestive heart failure\u003C/strong\u003E is an absolute contraindication as it is likely to worsen with an increased venous return following TIPS placement and is therefore a poor prognostic factor. This would need to be brought under control in this patient if TIPS was to be seriously considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatic encephalopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is not an indication for the TIPS procedure. Contrastingly, a history of hepatic encephalopathy is considered a \u003Cstrong\u003Erelative contraindication\u003C/strong\u003E to the TIPS procedure as the process of creating a shunt allows enteric neurotoxins to bypass first pass metabolism and reach the brain unaltered. Patients may be able to undergo the TIPS procedure for refractory ascites despite a previous history of hepatic encephalopathy, however this requires careful consideration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChild-Pugh Class C\u003C/strong\u003E patients with a score of 12 or higher are considered to have a very high risk of early death after the TIPS procedure, and therefore the procedure is advisable to withhold in this population group. The patient in this scenario has a total score of 8 (encephalopathy +1, ascites +2, raised bilirubin +2, raised INR +1, albumin +2) and is therefore classified as a Child-Pugh Class B patient. Whilst this would not preclude the procedure, it is certainly not an indication in and of itself.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Indications for the TIPS procedure include recurrent variceal bleeding and refractory ascites"],"references":["Copelan A, Kapoor B, Sands M. Transjugular intrahepatic portosystemic shunt: indications, contraindications, and patient work-up. Semin Intervent Radiol. 2014 Sep;31(3):235-42. doi: 10.1055/s-0034-1382790. PMID: 25177083; PMCID: PMC4139433.","Ferral H. The evaluation of the patient undergoing an elective transjugular intrahepatic portosystemic shunt procedure. Semin Intervent Radiol. 2005 Dec;22(4):266-70. doi: 10.1055/s-2005-925552. PMID: 21326704; PMCID: PMC3036299.","Gonzalez J. Why does hepatic encephalopathy develop after transjugular intrahepatic portosystemic (TIPS) shunt? Liver Fellow Network. 2023 Feb 20. Available from: https://www.aasld.org/liver-fellow-network/core-series/why-series/why-does-hepatic-encephalopathy-develop-after"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38300"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13429"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38300","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38300"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-12T14:09:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-12T14:11:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6037"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52910"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"181","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/181"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Cirrhosis","synonyms":["Liver c